english:
  title: A Record of the Pavilion of Wind and Verse in Sangju
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Sangju was once the kingdom of Sabal, and since it came under Silla's dominion, it has flourished as a great prefecture. For more than a thousand years since then, its mountains and waters have been among the most beautiful, and its people among the most distinguished of all the provinces. Yet it had never possessed grand pavilions or elegant towers—a testament to the simple and unadorned character of its people.

    In the year Gyeongseul under the Hongwu era, when the prefect Kim Nam-deok began renovating the public offices, he established an orchard to the northeast and constructed a pavilion within it. My former teacher, Hansan the Retired Minister Han, named it the Pavilion of Wind and Verse and wrote its record. The examination laureate Sungsan the Retired Scholar Tao also composed verses for it. Both were masters of letters of their age, and through their talents, the fame of this province was greatly enhanced.

    But in the year Gyeongsin, Japanese raiders invaded, and both official buildings and private homes fell to the flames of war. The following year, in Siniu, the deputy administrator began constructing the city walls, gathered the surviving people, and built a separate hall on the old foundation to receive visiting dignitaries. In the year Gyeongoh, Prefect Lee Boksi established new administrative offices, though there was no time to rebuild the pavilion.

    Now, under Prefect Song, working in harmony with Administrator Han Eom, they have swept away corruption, promoted benefit, cultivated virtue, and brought peace to the people. They have expanded the old pavilion site, raised a grand tower upon it, and restored both the Retired Minister's record and the Retired Scholar's verses to their former glory. The landscape of our province shines ever brighter.

    When a man of virtue travels bearing the insignia of his office, if he should pass through this place when spring has clothed the earth in new warmth and harmony flows like gentle light, how fortunate would our people be. This is our great hope for those who visit.

    Among the disciples of Confucius, each spoke of his aspirations, yet most concerned themselves with the mere execution of duties. Only Zengdian spoke of wandering in the spring breeze and returning home—and the Master expressed approval of his words. Scholars have noted in this the noble spirit of sage-kings Yao and Shun. For when the heart is free and boundless, moving with all things and granting each its proper place, then in governance there emerges a subtle harmony: the young are nurtured, the old find rest, travelers find welcome, and a gentle accord flows through all things. The people find joy in their fields and wells, as if constantly bathed in spring winds. The fruits of such rule flow with the great transformation of heaven and earth itself—and the rule of Yao and Shun was nothing more than this. Its source lies simply in a heart untethered by even the smallest private attachment.

    If those who bear office, when they ascend this tower, wash away the dust of worldly cares and worldly anxieties, then what burns the hand needs no spring to cool it, what tangles in complexity needs no counsel to untangle it. In those moments of quiet contemplation, observing the joy of wind and verse, they may gain insight into the unity of self and world—and how vast would be the transformation of their rule!

    As for the beautiful sights to be enjoyed from that tower, I am old, and if I should one day make that journey and stand upon it to witness the wind, I would surely add my own verses to those of Retired Scholar Tao.

    Written in the autumn, seventh month of the sixth year of Yonglo.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Pavilion of Wind and Verse' is named after Zengdian's famous words to Confucius about his aspiration to enjoy the spring breeze—a reference that elevates the pavilion as a place of moral and spiritual cultivation.
  - key: ''
    value: Gwon Geun's meditation on the pavilion becomes a reflection on ideal governance, drawing on the Confucian ideal of virtue-centered rule as exemplified by the legendary sage-kings Yao and Shun.
  - key: ''
    value: The tower's construction represents not merely architectural restoration but a restoration of civilized culture itself after the devastation of war, suggesting how physical beauty can restore social harmony.
